    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-d, Af, Ah-l). Stands are widespread in coastal settings from San Francisco Bay south to Santa Maria. Stands often occur in high salt marsh areas adjacent to stands of <i>Distichlis spicata,</i> and may occur in disturbed settings.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ag-i, Ak). Stands occur in alkali sinks of the Carrizo Plain and the Temblor Range with <i>Atriplex</i> spp., <i>D. spicata,</i> and many herb species (Twisselmann 1956). Some of these stands are regularly grazed.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ad, Ak-l, Aq, At, Av-z). Stands at Suisun Marsh in Solano Co. have high cover of <i>D. spicata</i> or annual grasses (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000). Those in the Sacramento-San Joaquin River delta contain <i>Bromus</i> spp., <i>D. spicata,</i> and <i>Lepidium latifolium</i> (Keeler-Wolf and Hickson 2007). Stands in alkali sinks of the Buena Vista-Tulare Basin (Twisselmann 1956), in alkali claypan vernal pools of the southern Solano-Colusa region, and in playas of the San Joaquin Valley (Twisselmann 1967) include <i>Lasthenia</i> spp., <i>Lepidium dictyotum</i> var. <i>acutidens,</i> and <i>Arthrocnemum subterminale</i> (Barbour et al. 2007b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ak-l). Stands occur in high salt marshes at Point Reyes, Tomales Bay, and San Pablo Bay.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb-c, Bg, Bj). On the mainland, stands in tidal marshes at Magu Lagoon in Ventura Co. have <i>D. spicata, Monanthochloe littoralis, Sarcocornia pacifica,</i> and <i>Suaeda taxifolia</i> (Keeler- Wolf and Evens 2006). On most of the Channel Islands, coastal wetlands of <i>Frankenia salina</i> and <i>Sarcocornia pacifica</i> occur with <i>Atriplex</i> spp., <i>D. spicata, Suaeda calceoliformis,</i> and <i>S. taxifolia</i> (Halvorson et al. 1996, Junak et al. 2007, Thorne 1967). On Santa Barbara and Anacapa Islands, stands of <i>S. taxifolia</i> occur with <i>F. salina, Hordeum murinum, Mesembryanthemum </i>spp., and other non-natives (Junak et al. 2007, Philbrick 1972).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
